answers.body_markdown:
&gt; Is Student the proper root here? 

An Aggregate is a consistency boundary. It exists to ensure that the entities contained therein are in a consistent, (i.e. valid) state as it pertains to your business rules. You haven&#39;t yet described any business rules or validations that should be ensured so I don&#39;t know that Student is the correct Aggregate. Read on...

&gt; Unfortunately EF core doesn&#39;t support filtering child objects yet.

EF Core does not support filtering child collections, but there might be other ways to accomplish this. Here is some pseuodcode:

    var query = 
        from s in ctx.Students
        where s.Id == 1 // Student filter here
        select new 
        {
            Student = s,
            Student = 
                from sa in s.StudentAttendances
                where sa. // Apply filter here
                select sa
        };

    // Perform the query against the DB and then return the Student object
    // EF will wire up the relationships for you and because you went to the
    // DB first before pulling the student, the data is local and you will
    // have the full tree
    var student = query.ToList().Select(x =&gt; x.Student).FirstOrDefault();

&gt; In this case should I treat the Attendance as different aggregate? So that I can query the attendance record independent of the student record?

It depends on your business rules. What are the lifetimes of the Student and Attendance? Can the Student have any number of Attendances? Think more about your Write Use Cases and less about your Read Use Cases. Do you need to load StudentAttendances at all? Is that simply a Read Use Case? 

Also consider whether ONE Student Aggregate is sufficient. Should you load all of the Attendance records when you simply want to change a phone number? Just as we have Bounded Contexts, you might consider having Bounded Aggregates, e.g. vertical partitions of an Aggregate within a Bounded Context splitting what sounds like one single, large concept into several smaller concepts. 

You can have: 

 - A Student Aggregate with a filtered list of Attendances (as illustrated above)
 - A StudentAttendance Aggregate (as you mentioned)
 - A StudentWithAttendance Aggregate which is separate from the Student Aggregate and serves a different use case

&gt; I am missing something here? Should I rethink my design?

It depends. Generally, I would suggest thinking more at a Domain level and less at a DB level. Think more about Writes than Reads. 

EF forces us, in some ways to think in a relational way even as we model our Domain, but we should fight that urge and relegate EF to a simple persistence mechanism where possible and not let it drive our Domain design decisions.

